# Generic Rules

## Communication
- Keep responses brief and action-focused. No preamble, filler, or sycophancy.
- Plain, direct language. Avoid buzzwords like "leverage", "robust", "seamless", "comprehensive".
- No emojis unless explicitly requested.
- After substantive edits, end with a short bullet summary of what changed.
- Cite exact file paths (and line numbers when relevant) when discussing code.

## Git / source control
- NEVER run `git add`, `git commit`, or `git push`. Instead, print the exact commands for the user to run. Use git add {file/path}, not "." or "-A"
- Keep commit messages short and concrete. No verbose AI prose, no marketing language.
- These git operations are allowed, but ASK BEFORE running:
  - merge conflict resolution
  - branch creation / `git checkout` / switching branches
  - `git rebase`
- Never bypass hooks (`--no-verify`) or force push without explicit user instruction.
- when you make a branch, prefix it with ccrozier-{whatever}

### Commit message style

```
GOOD: fix null check in auth middleware

BAD: This commit comprehensively addresses a critical issue by introducing
     a robust null-safety enhancement to seamlessly improve the
     authentication middleware's resilience.
```

## Safety and process
- Ask before any destructive shell command (`rm -rf`, `DROP TABLE`, force push, mass file deletion, etc.).
- Don't fabricate APIs, functions, packages, or versions. Verify by reading code or docs first.
- Read a file before editing it. Don't guess at contents.
- Don't make unrelated changes or expand scope beyond what was requested.
- Ask before large refactors or multi-file restructures.

## Code style
- No obvious or narrating comments (e.g. `// increment counter`, `// import module`).
- Prefer editing existing files over creating new ones.

## Bugs found while working on a task
When you discover a bug unrelated to the requested change:

1. Decide if the bug BLOCKS the requested task.
   - Blocking = the requested feature/fix cannot work correctly without addressing it.
2. If BLOCKING: document the bug (what, where, why it blocks), fix it in the current PR, and call it out in the PR description under a "Drive-by fixes" or "Also fixed" section.
3. If NOT BLOCKING: do NOT fix it. Document it for the user with:
   - file path + line(s)
   - short description of the bug
   - suggested fix (1-2 lines)
   - a note that it is unresolved and recommend a follow-up issue.
4. Never silently fix unrelated bugs.

## PRs and issues (give text, not commands)
- Do NOT run `gh pr create`, `gh issue create`, or any git/gh command that opens or pushes PRs/issues.
- Instead, output the text the user will paste into the GitHub/GitLab UI (markdown format)
- Always provide a title AND a body, clearly labeled.
- Word limits (hard caps):
  - PR body: under 100 words
  - Issue body: under 50 words
  - Title: under 12 words, imperative mood, no trailing period
- No marketing language, no emojis, no "This PR comprehensively..." style intros.
- Body structure:
  - PR: 1-2 line summary, then short bullets for what changed and how to test.
  - Issue: 1-line problem, 1-line expected behavior, 1-line repro (if relevant).

### Example PR output

```
TITLE: fix null check in auth middleware

BODY:
Auth middleware crashed when `req.user` was undefined on public routes.

Changes:
- Add null guard in `authMiddleware` before role lookup
- Add unit test for unauthenticated request

Test: `npm test -- auth.middleware`
```

### Example issue output

```
TITLE: auth middleware crashes on public routes

BODY:
`authMiddleware` throws when `req.user` is undefined.
Expected: skip role check and call `next()`.
Repro: GET /health while logged out.
```